[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the book lead against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks, and after the diamond lead your \DA-Q-6 behind West is comfortable — but the count is not: to reach nine, the club suit — dummy's \CK-J-T-7 over your ace — must deliver FOUR tricks. A missing queen with company. Ask yourself: will one finesse be enough, and if not, what does the suit need from you?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D4 to dummy's jack. Clubs now, and patiently: cash the ACE first, then lead low and pass it to dummy's TEN — it holds, West ducking. Return to hand and lead clubs again: this time West's queen climbs, and dummy's king captures it. Back once more, and the JACK picks up West's nine on the way. Four club tricks without a loser — the suit was hooked THREE times — and with the diamonds and top cards the count reads nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] That was the REPEATED FINESSE: a guarded queen never falls to one hook, so you led toward the K-J-T again and again, spending an entry each trip. Same lesson, same discipline — the finesse is not an event, it is a route you may have to travel more than once. Three boards down.}
