[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DJ, top of your \DJ-T sequence — a safe, solid start against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks, and this time the question sits in the TRUMP suit itself: your \SA-J-6-4-2 opposite dummy's Q-T-5, missing the king. Play ace-and-out and a guarded king beats you; so ask the exam question — which opponent do you play for the king, and how do you arrange to lead the suit so his king is trapped?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The defense cashes its two top diamonds and shifts. Win, and play trumps the right way round: from DUMMY, running the TEN. East covers with the king — your ace captures it — and now dummy's queen and your jack draw the rest. No trump trick lost. Set up the clubs, concede the \HK, and ten tricks are in.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] A simple finesse — but in trumps, where it is easiest to forget that "lead toward the honor" applies just as much. Running the ten through East kept the king from ever scoring; ace-first would have promoted it. Same tool as board one, different suit — the exam likes disguises.}
